A very large model pulse rocket being administered to by none other than Freeman Dyson.<br>
<br>
<br>
For all you model rocket builders here's an idea you can try at home. I'm assuming you're licensed ofcourse. Being a minority group the laws regulating model rocket use have become prohibitively difficult to meet in some countries. But for the many addicts who have fought through the red tape to keep their exciting hobby here is something which might interest you.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.upei.ca/~physics/p261/projects/spaceprop/ORION1.JPG"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.upei.ca/~physics/p261/projects/spaceprop/ORION2.JPG"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
Unless you have access to Plutonium I suggest using chemical explosives for your first models. <br>
<br>
Model pulse rockets were first experimented with back in the late 50's to test the feasibility of Orion. An atomic bomb driven spaceship which might have massed around 10,000 tons if built and would have been launched from Nevada flats testing grounds. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://a52.g.akamaitech.net/f/52/827/1d/www.space.com/images/h_battleship_01,1.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
You can read more of Orion in other threads. By far the most advanced engine ever concieved by the human mind and in a class of its own as far as performance went. Such vehicles could have theoretically lifted entire cities. Battlestar Galactica eat your heart out.<br>
Pulse rocketry is now recieving funding from congress as JPL researches its applicability to chemical rockets. The advantages being better control and less heat eradication problems. Instead of a continuous burn the rocket fires pulses. Not disimilar to a car engine. This allows time for heat to dissipate between blasts.<br>
<br>
Model pulse rocketry(<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.angelfire.com/stars2/projectorion/testmodels">link</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->) started and died in the late 50's/early 60's so this offers a unique opportunity for those with imagination to make something perhaps totally original. The concept has hardly been experimented with at all so if you want to really flex your creativity then this could be the chance to explore a new style of rocket propulsion. If you enjoy a challenge and like building model rockets then this could be right down your alley.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://a676.g.akamai.net/f/676/987/12h/photos.netclubs.com/live/photos/Clubs/t/p/tpeidaeb7nah3e2e0188nkppm4/OrionNow2.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
As you can see from this logo, the concept requires you to delve into entirely new areas of engineering. The explosive propellant must be separated into pellets or squirted in measured quantities. The suspension system should you require one might double as a method of refueling a pump for firing the next pulse. The pusher plate has to be made strong enough to withstand rather powerful detonations if using solid explosive such as TNT.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.nasm.edu/nasm/dsh/artifacts/images/RM/A19721008000.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
In 1959 engineers conducted the program's only live test at Point Loma, California, a former Atlas missile test site. Popularly known to the project engineers and scientists as Hot Rod, the Orion test vehicle fired five rapid, successive explosions (using conventional charges not nuclear bombs). The explosion shock waves were directed at a well-protected pusher plate, driving the vehicle forward. The vehicle was then recovered by parachute. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.angelfire.com/stars2/projectorion/">More </a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->about Project Orion.<br>
<br>
